Definition of [Gamification](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamification) on Wikipedia.

Gamification is the ability to apply game elements and game design techniques into non-game context. Essentially thinking outside the box and enabling us to use skills from games in real life situations.

Some major game elements, with descriptions and examples, can be found on [Google Docs](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0AgC8f8dxYGaSdG80ZUEwX0pUTHZXU0FJMGJ0Zkl5a0E#gid=0).

A definition of Gamification from WePlay: [More Than Just Badges: We Playâ€™s Definition of Gamification](http://weplay.co/more-than-just-badges-we-plays-definition-of-gamification/)

Gamification is a contested concept. Some say it is a term hijacked by marketers to mean something far more shallow, far less interesting than originally intended, usually something like, "Solve a wide variety of business problems, by encouraging highly valuable user behavior." See e.g.,  https://plus.google.com/+TimOReilly/posts/TFvQ2FDTKy5

The term gamification has three important concepts:
<ol>
<li>Game elements</li>
<li>Game design techniques</li>
<li>Non-game context</li>
</ol>
